<paragraph id="8BC23695FF958239FF51730B92D9F9FD" blockId="12.[160,711,1580,1606]" box="[160,711,1580,1606]" pageId="12" pageNumber="295">
<heading id="D08A81F9FF958239FF51730B92D9F9FD" bold="true" box="[160,711,1580,1606]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="12" pageNumber="295" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF958239FF51730B92D9F9FD" bold="true" box="[160,711,1580,1606]" pageId="12" pageNumber="295">
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF958239FF51730B91AEF9FD" box="[160,432,1580,1606]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Aechmea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="295" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="distichantha">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF958239FF51730B91AEF9FD" bold="true" box="[160,432,1580,1606]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="295">Aechmea distichantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a keystone species
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC23695FF958238FF5173479432FDD1" blockId="12.[159,1155,1632,1727]" lastBlockId="13.[159,1156,142,1207]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="296" pageId="12" pageNumber="295">
Among plants, until now, mainly trees have been labelled as keystone species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF958239FBD073479109F927" author="Manning AD &amp; Fischer J &amp; Lindenmayer DB" pageId="12" pageNumber="295" pagination="311 - 321" refId="ref11285" refString="Manning AD, Fischer J, Lindenmayer DB. 2006. Scattered trees are keystone structures - implications for conservation. Biol Conserv. 32 (3): 311 - 321. doi: 10.1016 / j. biocon. 2006.04.023." type="journal article" year="2006">Manning et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF958239FED973A491EAF927" author="Stagoll K &amp; Lindenmayer DB &amp; Knight E &amp; Fischer J &amp; Manning AD" box="[296,500,1667,1692]" pageId="12" pageNumber="295" pagination="115 - 122" refId="ref12988" refString="Stagoll K, Lindenmayer DB, Knight E, Fischer J, Manning AD. 2012. Large trees are keystone structures in urban parks. Conserv Lett. 5: 115 - 122." type="journal article" year="2012">Stagoll et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). Palms and figs have drawn the attention of researchers (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF958239FF54738191C1F904" author="Lambert FR &amp; Marshall AG" box="[165,479,1702,1727]" pageId="12" pageNumber="295" pagination="793 - 809" refId="ref11107" refString="Lambert FR, Marshall AG. 1991. Keystone characteristics of bird-dispersed Ficus in a Malaysian lowland rain forest. J Ecol. 79 (3): 793 - 809. doi: 10.2307 / 2260668." type="journal article" year="1991">Lambert and Marshall 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF958239FE01738192B9F904" author="Mills L &amp; Soule M &amp; Doak D" box="[496,679,1702,1727]" pageId="12" pageNumber="295" pagination="219 - 224" refId="ref11582" refString="Mills L, Soule M, Doak D. 1993. The keystone-species concept in ecology and conservation. BioScience. 43: 219 - 224." type="journal article" year="1993">Mills et al. 1993</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF958239FD497381939DF904" author="Nason JD &amp; Herre EA &amp; Hamrick JL" box="[696,899,1702,1727]" pageId="12" pageNumber="295" pagination="685 - 687" refId="ref11935" refString="Nason JD, Herre EA, Hamrick JL. 1998. The breeding structure of a tropical keystone plant resource. Nature. 391: 685 - 687." type="journal article" year="1998">Nason et al. 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF958239FC6573819458F904" author="Stevenson P" box="[916,1094,1702,1727]" pageId="12" pageNumber="295" pagination="37 - 57" refId="ref13077" refString="Stevenson P. 2005. Potential keystone plant species for the frugivore community at Tinigua Park, Colombia. In: Dew JL, Boubli JP, editors. Tropical fruits and frugivores: the search for strong interactors. Dordrecht: Springer; p. 37 - 57." type="book chapter" year="2005">Stevenson 2005</bibRefCitation>
) and emblematic palm species such as the threatened 
<collectingCountry id="F36A7605FF948238FD1575A99378FF1C" box="[740,870,142,167]" name="Madagascar" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
Triangle Palm 
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FBEB75A990F4FF71" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Neodypsis decaryi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FEF375969276FF71" author="Ratsirarson J &amp; Silander JJA" box="[258,616,177,202]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="737 - 745" refId="ref12376" refString="Ratsirarson J, Silander JJA. 1996. Reproductive biology of the threatened Madagascar triangle palm: neodypsis decaryi Jumelle. Biotropica. 28: 737 - 745." type="journal article" year="1996">Ratsirarson and Silander 1996</bibRefCitation>
), the Neotropical dioecious 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FC367596949DFF71" box="[967,1155,177,202]" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Maurita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flexuosa">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FC367596949DFF71" box="[967,1155,177,202]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Maurita flexuosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FF5475F3917FFF56" author="Brightsmith DJ" box="[165,353,212,237]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="296 - 305" refId="ref8585" refString="Brightsmith DJ. 2005. Parrot nesting in southeastern Peru: seasonal patterns and keystone trees. Wilson J Ornithol. 117: 296 - 305." type="journal article" year="2005">Brightsmith 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FE9E75F39263FF56" author="van der Hoek Y &amp; Alvarez Solas S &amp; Penuela MC" box="[367,637,212,237]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="539 - 551" refId="ref13328" refString="van der Hoek Y, Alvarez Solas S, Penuela MC. 2019. The palm Mauritia flexuosa, a keystone plant resource on multiple fronts. Biodivers Conserv. 28: 539 - 551." type="journal article" year="2019">van der Hoek et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FD6075F3933AFF56" box="[657,804,212,237]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Euterpe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="edulis">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FD6075F3933AFF56" box="[657,804,212,237]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Euterpe edulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Atlantic forest (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FBEB75F39146FEB4" author="de Barros Leite A &amp; Brancalion PH &amp; Guevara R &amp; Galetti M" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="615 - 618" refId="ref9648" refString="de Barros Leite A, Brancalion PH, Guevara R, Galetti M. 2012. Differential seed germination of a keystone palm (Euterpe edulis) dispersed by avian frugivores. J Trop Ecol. 28 (6): 615 - 618. doi: 10.1017 / S 0266467412000594." type="journal article" year="2012">de Barros Leite et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FE6E75D19274FEB4" box="[415,618,246,271]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Phoenix" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dactylifera">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FE6E75D19274FEB4" box="[415,618,246,271]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Phoenix dactylifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Date palm) in 
<collectingCountry id="F36A7605FF948238FCD575D1936CFEB4" box="[804,882,246,271]" name="Mexico" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Mexico</collectingCountry>
oases of 
<collectingRegion id="49B9F877FF948238FC1475D1949DFEB4" box="[997,1155,246,271]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Baja California</collectingRegion>
peninsula, (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FEEB743E91C9FE89" author="De Grenade R" box="[282,471,281,306]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="59 - 67" refId="ref9700" refString="De Grenade R. 2013. Date palm as a keystone species in Baja California peninsula, Mexico oases. J Arid Environ. 94: 59 - 67. doi: 10.1016 / j. jaridenv. 2013.02.008." type="journal article" year="2013">
De 
<collectingCountry id="F36A7605FF948238FECE743E9185FE89" box="[319,411,281,306]" name="Grenada" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Grenade</collectingCountry>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
) have been identified as keystone plant species. Other arboreal species such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FEBE741B9226FEEE" box="[335,568,316,341]" class="Pinopsida" family="Araucariaceae" genus="Araucaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angustifolia">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FEBE741B9226FEEE" box="[335,568,316,341]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Araucaria angustifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Atlantic forests (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FCC9741B941FFEEE" author="Bogoni JA &amp; Muniz-Tagliari M &amp; Peroni N &amp; Peres CA" box="[824,1025,316,341]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="106778" refId="ref8472" refString="Bogoni JA, Muniz-Tagliari M, Peroni N, Peres CA. 2020. Testing the keystone plant resource role of a flagship subtropical tree species (Araucaria angustifolia) in the Brazilian Atlantic Forest. Ecol Indic. 118: 106778. doi: 10.1016 / j. ecolind. 2020.106778." type="journal article" year="2020">Bogoni et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
), the 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FBB0741B949DFEEE" box="[1089,1155,316,341]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Parkia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FBB0741B949DFEEE" box="[1089,1155,316,341]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Parkia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus in Amazonian forests (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FE0E7479929EFECC" author="Peres CA" box="[511,640,350,375]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="287 - 317" refId="ref12266" refString="Peres CA. 2000. Identifying keystone plant resources in tropical forests: the case of gums from Parkia pods. J Trop Ecol. 16: 287 - 317." type="journal article" year="2000">Peres 2000</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FD6C747992FCFECC" box="[669,738,350,375]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FD6C747992FCFECC" box="[669,738,350,375]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Acacia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
trees in Negev desert ecosystems (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FF5474A691F9FE21" author="Munzbergova Z &amp; Ward D" box="[165,487,385,410]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="227 - 236" refId="ref11750" refString="Munzbergova Z, Ward D. 2002. Acacia trees as keystone species in Negev desert ecosystems. J Veg Sci. 13: 227 - 236." type="journal article" year="2002">Munzbergova and Ward 2002</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FDD574A692F2FE21" authorityName="Harms" authorityYear="1926" box="[548,748,385,410]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Dipteryx" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="micrantha">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FDD574A692F2FE21" box="[548,748,385,410]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Dipteryx micrantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FD0974A6937FFE21" box="[760,865,385,410]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
) in tropical lowland forests in 
<collectingCountry id="F36A7605FF948238FF4B748390F2FE06" box="[186,236,420,445]" name="Peru" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FF06748391AFFE06" author="Brightsmith DJ" box="[247,433,420,445]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="296 - 305" refId="ref8585" refString="Brightsmith DJ. 2005. Parrot nesting in southeastern Peru: seasonal patterns and keystone trees. Wilson J Ornithol. 117: 296 - 305." type="journal article" year="2005">Brightsmith 2005</bibRefCitation>
) were also described playing that role in ecosystems. Finally, lianas, vascular epiphytes and climber plants have been reported as well as keystone species in forests (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FF0274CE918CFDB9" author="Nadkarni NM" box="[243,402,489,514]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="70 - 78" refId="ref11869" refString="Nadkarni NM. 1994. Diversity of species and interactions in the upper tree canopy of forest ecosystems. Am Zool. 34: 70 - 78." type="journal article" year="1994">Nadkarni 1994</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FE6C74CE928EFDB9" author="Diaz-Martin Z &amp; Swamy V &amp; Terborgh J &amp; Alvarez-Loayza P &amp; Cornejo F" box="[413,656,489,514]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="291 - 301" refId="ref9914" refString="Diaz-Martin Z, Swamy V, Terborgh J, Alvarez-Loayza P, Cornejo F. 2014. Identifying keystone plant resources in an Amazonian forest using a long-term fruit-fall record. J Trop Ecol. 30 (4): 291 - 301. doi: 10.1017 / S 0266467414000248." type="journal article" year="2014">Diaz-Martin et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Even though many 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FC8874CE9414FDB9" box="[889,1034,489,514]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bromeliaceae</taxonomicName>
have been suggested as keystone species in forests (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FD98772B9301FD9E" author="Richardson BA" box="[617,799,524,549]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="321 - 336" refId="ref12465" refString="Richardson BA. 1999. The bromeliad microcosm and the assessment of faunal diversity in a Neotropical forest 1. Biotropica. 31: 321 - 336." type="journal article" year="1999">Richardson 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FCDC772B93DFFD9E" author="Benzing DH" box="[813,961,524,549]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" refId="ref8213" refString="Benzing DH. 2000. Bromeliaceae. Profile of an adaptive radiation. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press." type="book" year="2000">Benzing 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FC3F772B90CAFDFC" author="Shackleton CM &amp; Ticktin T &amp; Cunningham AB" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="4" refId="ref12901" refString="Shackleton CM, Ticktin T, Cunningham AB. 2018. Nontimber forest products as ecological and biocultural keystone species. Ecol Soc. 23: 4." type="journal article" year="2018">Shackleton et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
), to the best of our knowledge 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FDC9770992CBFDFC" box="[568,725,558,583]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Aechmea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="distichantha">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FDC9770992CBFDFC" box="[568,725,558,583]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">A. distichantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
results in the first facultative epiphytic herbaceous plant (i.e. either terrestrial or epiphytic) reported as a keystone species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C367651EFF948238FF317753949AFB0C" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC23695FF948238FF3177539201FC5C" blockId="13.[159,1156,142,1207]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">
This study showed the interactions of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FD8577539306FD36" box="[628,792,628,653]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Aechmea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="distichantha">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FD8577539306FD36" box="[628,792,628,653]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">A. distichantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with many animal species from different taxonomic groups. On the assumption that the analyses of the linking structure of species are an appropriate criterion for determining the keystone species status (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FBC8779E9105FD4E" author="Kotliar NB &amp; Baker BW &amp; Whicker AD &amp; Plumb G" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="177 - 192" refId="ref10909" refString="Kotliar NB, Baker BW, Whicker AD, Plumb G. 1999. A critical review of assumptions about the prairie dog as a keystone species. Environ Manage. 24 (2): 177 - 192. doi: 10.1007 / s 002679900225." type="journal article" year="1999">Kotliar et al. 1999</bibRefCitation>
), this bromeliad species could be considered a keystone species, and thus being very important in regulating biodiversity (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FD4977D9932AFCAC" author="Davic RD" box="[696,820,766,791]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" refId="ref9621" refString="Davic RD. 2003. Linking keystone species and functional groups: a new operational definition of the keystone species concept. Conserv Ecol. 7." type="book" year="2003">Davic 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Identifying keystone species in threatened ecosystems (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FE3C760692A7FC81" author="Carnevale NJ &amp; Alzugaray C &amp; Di Leo N" box="[461,697,801,826]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="47 - 56" refId="ref9033" refString="Carnevale NJ, Alzugaray C, Di Leo N. 2007. Estudio de la deforestacion en la Cuna Boscosa santafesina mediante teledeteccion espacial. Quebracho. 14: 47 - 56." type="journal article" year="2007">Carnevale et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FD377606938BFC81" author="Hansen MC &amp; Potapov PV &amp; Moore R &amp; Hancher M &amp; Turubanova SAA &amp; Tyukavina A &amp; Thau D &amp; Stehman SV &amp; Goetz SJ &amp; Loveland TR" box="[710,917,801,826]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="850 - 853" refId="ref10448" refString="Hansen MC, Potapov PV, Moore R, Hancher M, Turubanova SAA, Tyukavina A, Thau D, Stehman SV, Goetz SJ, Loveland TR, et al. 2013. High-resolution global maps of 21 st-century forest cover change. Science. 342 (6160): 850 - 853. doi: 10.1126 / science. 1244693." type="journal article" year="2013">Hansen et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
) is an important task that ecologists should assume because of the documented importance of these species in conservation or biodiversity protection (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FDAD76419319FCC4" author="Mills L &amp; Soule M &amp; Doak D" box="[604,775,870,895]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="219 - 224" refId="ref11582" refString="Mills L, Soule M, Doak D. 1993. The keystone-species concept in ecology and conservation. BioScience. 43: 219 - 224." type="journal article" year="1993">Mills et al. 1993</bibRefCitation>
), as well as by their important role by providing ecosystem services to humans (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FD3076AE9381FC19" author="Ladino G &amp; Ospina-Bautista F &amp; Estevez Varon J &amp; Jerabkova L &amp; Kratina P" box="[705,927,905,930]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="7360 - 7372" refId="ref11059" refString="Ladino G, Ospina-Bautista F, Estevez Varon J, Jerabkova L, Kratina P. 2019. Ecosystem services provided by bromeliad plants: a systematic review. Ecol Evol. 9 (12): 7360 - 7372. doi: 10.1002 / ece 3.5296." type="journal article" year="2019">Ladino et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
) and by providing resources to many species of animals that interact with it and, as it happens with other species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FF0E76E9920DFC5C" author="van der Hoek Y &amp; Alvarez Solas S &amp; Penuela MC" box="[255,531,974,999]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="539 - 551" refId="ref13328" refString="van der Hoek Y, Alvarez Solas S, Penuela MC. 2019. The palm Mauritia flexuosa, a keystone plant resource on multiple fronts. Biodivers Conserv. 28: 539 - 551." type="journal article" year="2019">van der Hoek et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC23695FF948238FF3176D6949AFB0C" blockId="13.[159,1156,142,1207]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">
Summing up, this review provides new perspectives about the fauna associated with 
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D16FF948238FF6E71339194FB96" box="[159,394,1044,1069]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Aechmea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="distichantha">
<emphasis id="B909EA87FF948238FF6E71339194FB96" box="[159,394,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="296">Aechmea distichantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a keystone plant species, by listing the animal species and showing the importance of arthropods, by taxonomically describing this fauna assembly, by revealing the pattern of different groups in terms of their interactions with the plant as it is suggested for a correct review (
<bibRefCitation id="EFEC4B64FF948238FE69715B9209FB2E" author="Sayer EJ" box="[408,535,1148,1173]" pageId="13" pageNumber="296" pagination="2278 - 2281" refId="ref12633" refString="Sayer EJ. 2018. The anatomy of an excellent review paper. Funct Ecol. 32: 2278 - 2281." type="journal article" year="2018">Sayer 2018</bibRefCitation>
), and finally by showing the need of improving the taxonomical identification in future studies, as this is an important gap in current knowledge.
</paragraph>
